Women Employment Status

Denise Bishevsky

2021-07-18

Introduction

Information about the data:

  • This data set was taken from Tidytuesday.
  • The data contains information about employed persons by industry, sex, race, and occupation.

Goals:

As an engineering and management student and woman who will soon enter the job market I was interested in raising my awareness of the current market situation. So I decided to focus on answering the following questions:

  • What are the income gaps between women and men?
  • How has Covid-19 affected the various industries?
  • What is the percentage of women in management positions and in what industries?
  • And is it possible to build a model that predicts the earn of each person according to his data?

# I will use this theme for the graphs later on
costum_theme <- function() {
  theme(
    axis.text = element_text(colour = "#555555", family = "Montserrat"),
    plot.title = element_text(colour = "#271729", size = 18, vjust = 1,hjust = 0.5, family = "Montserrat"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5, margin = unit(c(0,0,0,1), "cm")),
    axis.title = element_text(colour = "#271729", size = 13, family = "Montserrat"),
    panel.grid.major.x = element_line(colour = "#e4e4e4"),
    panel.grid.minor.x = element_line(colour = "#e4e4e4"),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "#e4e4e4"),
    panel.grid.minor.y = element_line(colour = "#e4e4e4"),
    strip.text = element_text(family = "Montserrat", colour = "white"),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "#271729"),
    axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "#271729")

  )
}

Transformation and Visualization

Let’s get down to business!
In the previous chapter we saw that the earn table has a column named median_weekly_earn. To start, I would like to examine what is the difference between women’s and men’s median weekly earnings:

# Draw histogram  
weekly_earn_plot<- earn %>%
    group_by(year, sex) %>%
    filter(sex!="Both Sexes") %>% 
  # calculate the median weekly earn across all the women and men groups
    summarise(median_earn = median(median_weekly_earn)) %>% 
  #plot
    ggplot(aes(x=year, y= median_earn, fill=fct_rev(sex))) + 
    geom_col(position="dodge", show.legend = T) +
    scale_color_manual(values=c("#3abcff","#ff7be5")) +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(10))+
    labs(y="MEDIAN WEEKLY EARNINGS",
         x= "YEAR",
         fill = "SEX",
         title=  "WHO EARNS MORE?",
         subtitle = "MEDIAN WEEKLY EARNINGS OF MEN AND WOMEN")+
  theme_minimal()
weekly_earn_plot + costum_theme()

We can clearly see a number of things:

  • First, over the years the median weekly earnings of both sexes have increased quite linearly.

  • It is noticeable that the median weekly earnings of men are higher than of women.

Let’s examine whether there are differences in the earnings between the sexes according to their ages:

# Select the ages that don't overlaping

                 "35 to 44 years","45 to 54 years","55 to 64 years","65 years and over")

women_earn_by_age <- earn %>%
  group_by(sex, age) %>%
  filter(sex!="Both Sexes") %>%
  filter(age %in% age_to_plot) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=age, y=median_weekly_earn , fill = sex)) +

  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  labs(y="MEDIAN WEEKLY EARNINGS", x= "AGE", fill = "SEX",
        title = "HOW DOES AGE MATTER?",

women_earn_by_age + costum_theme()

  • In this graph we see the variance of the weekly median earnings of different groups of women and men separated by their ages and distributed by years.

  • Up to the age of 35-44 the median weekly earnings of both sexes increased with a sharp positive slope. Men’s earnings continue to grow even until age 45-54. Thereafter, the earnings of both sexes remain stable and at age 65 and above it decreases.

  • One can see that the median weekly earnings of women is always lower than that of men but the significant gap starts from the ages of 35-44.

Statistical Hypothesis Testing

Two-Sample Proportions Test

Continuing from the last graph, I would like to check if the proportion of women holding managerial positions is equal to that of men.
To do this, I will create a comparison table between the number of women and men in managerial and non-managerial positions and run a two- sample proportion test. This hypothesis test will help to check whether the proportions in the two groups are equal.
Let: \[ P_1 = \text{The proportion of women who are managers} \] \[ P_2 = \text{The proportion of men who are managers} \] That is, our hypotheses will be:

\[ H_0 : P_1 - P_2 = 0 \] \[ H_1 : P_1 - P_2 \neq 0 \]

employees_2020 <- employed %>%
  filter(year == 2020) %>%
  filter(industry != "Mining, quarrying, and oil and gas extraction")%>%
  filter(!is.na(employ_n)) %>%
  filter(category == "Sex") %>%
  group_by(race_gender, major_occupation) %>%
  summarize(employees = sum(employ_n))

# calculate amount of men that are managers-------------------------------------
df <- employees_2020 %>%
  filter(major_occupation == "Management, professional, and related occupations",
         race_gender == "Men")
  
men_managers<- sum(df$employees) 
#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

# calculate amount of women that are managers
df <- employees_2020 %>%
  filter(major_occupation == "Management, professional, and related occupations",
         race_gender == "Women")
  
women_managers<- sum(df$employees) 
#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
# calculate amount of men that are not managers
df <- employees_2020 %>%
  filter(major_occupation != "Management, professional, and related occupations",
         race_gender == "Men")
  
men_not_managers<- sum(df$employees)
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# calculate amount of women that are not managers
df <- employees_2020 %>%
  filter(major_occupation != "Management, professional, and related occupations",
         race_gender == "Women")
  
women_not_managers<- sum(df$employees)     
#-------------------------------------------------------------------------------  

# create a table
managers_2020<- matrix(c(women_managers, women_not_managers, men_managers, men_not_managers), ncol = 2, byrow = T)
rownames(managers_2020) <- c("WOMEN","MEN")
colnames(managers_2020) <- c("MANAGERS", "NOT MANAGERS")
managers_2020 = as.table(managers_2020)
managers_2020
      MANAGERS NOT MANAGERS
WOMEN 36599000     48734000
MEN   36468000     65597000

Now we are all set and can run the proportionality test:

prop.test(managers_2020, alternative = "two.sided")

    2-sample test for equality of proportions with continuity correction

data:  managers_2020
X-squared = 1001458, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: two.sided
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.07145423 0.07173475
sample estimates:
   prop 1    prop 2 
0.4288962 0.3573017
  • As can be seen, at a confidence level of 95 percent, the p-value is less than the significance level of 0.05 therefore we will reject the null hypothesis. In other words, it turns out that in 2020 the proportion of women holding managerial positions was greater than that of men and it can be seen that it was 42% compared to 35%.

To illustrate this visually I will draw a graph:

# Draw barplot that shows the difference between the amount of
# men and women in management and non- management professions
colors <- c('#fbb4ae', '#b3cde3')
barplot(managers_2020,
        beside = TRUE,
        col= colors,
        legend = TRUE,
        args.legend = list(bty = "n", x = "top", ncol = 2),
        yaxp=c(0, max(managers_2020), 5))

  • In this case it can be seen quite clearly that indeed the proportion of women holding managerial positions compared to man is greater.

Modeling

I would like to build a model that will predict the median weekly earnings of each person. To do this I use a linear regression model.

At the beginning of our journey we saw that as the years go by, the median weekly earnings increases and so, for starters, I will try to predict it using the "year" column.

# Clear the data set from "Both Sexes" variable 
earn_for_model <- earn %>%
  filter(age %in% age_to_plot,
         sex != "Both Sexes")

linear_model_1 <- lm(median_weekly_earn ~year, data = earn_for_model,weights = n_persons)
summary(linear_model_1)

    We will draw a graph that illustrates why this happened:
earn_for_model %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=median_weekly_earn, x= year))+
  geom_point(size = 2)+
  scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  stat_smooth(method = "lm")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(10))+
  theme_minimal()+ 
  costum_theme()

- The graph does justify the fact that the model we built requires improvement. You can see that the points are scattered in a way that looks like groups. This means that more explanatory variables need to be added to the model to get better results.

In the graphs we drew in the visualization section we saw that there is a relationship between sex, age and the median weekly earnings
It’s time to add them to the model:

Note that in the next model uses naive addition of explanatory variables to the model, assuming all variables are independent. I will expand on that later.

linear_model_2 <- lm(median_weekly_earn ~ age + sex + year, data = earn_for_model, weights = n_persons)

summary(linear_model_2)

What a huge improvement!

  • The R-squared increased to 0.9297 and the Adjusted R-squared to 0.9288
  • In addition, it can be seen that the model and all its explanatory variables are significant.
  • The estimators also behaves in the way that we expected them to behave - The base case is a man at the age of 16-19 and compare to him the older ages. The median weekly earnings rise until the age of 65 where it takes a slight dip. Also the earnings goes up over the years and finally if you are a woman your earnings are lower.

I will illustrate this also visually:

colors <- c("#f8b365","#739fbe","#ef7e73","#bebada","#fbf4b5","#80beb3","#8ce5d4")

earn_for_model %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=median_weekly_earn, x= year,
             group=age,

  scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  stat_smooth(method = "lm")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(10))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#ef9014", "#FC4E07","#4dba4d","#ff88d5","#8edcef" ,"#FFCA22","#00AFBB"))+
  theme_minimal()+ 
  costum_theme()

But we can do better!

As I mentioned earlier, the latter model used a naive addition of explanatory variables to the model on the assumption that sex and age are independent variables. Although their addition has improved the model, it does not take into account that there are differences between women and men according to their age. To improve this we will add an interaction to the age-sex variables in the model:

earn_for_model <- earn %>%
  filter(age %in% age_to_plot,
         sex != "Both Sexes")

linear_model_3 <- lm(median_weekly_earn ~ age*sex + year, data = earn_for_model, weights = n_persons)
summary(linear_model_3)

  • As you can see the model has improved even more.
  • The R-squared increased to 0.9737 and the Adjusted R-squared to 0.9731.
  • The standard error decreased from 137500 to 84460.
  • The model and all its explanatory variables are significant except from “age20 to 24 years:sexWomen” and “age25 to 34 years:sexWomen” which we have understood from earlier graphs that the significant difference begins only after the age of 35.
  • And as we expected the model shows that women of different ages will benefit differently from men at same age.

Here is the graph of the final result:

colors <- c("#f8b365","#739fbe","#ef7e73","#bebada","#fbf4b5","#80beb3","#8ce5d4")

earn_for_model %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=median_weekly_earn, x= year,
             group=interaction(age, sex),
             color = age,
            linetype=sex))+
  geom_point(size = 2, aes(shape=sex))+
  scale_y_log10(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"))+
  stat_smooth(method = "lm")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(10))+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#ef9014", "#FC4E07","#4dba4d","#ff88d5","#8edcef" ,"#FFCA22","#00AFBB"))+
  theme_minimal()+ 
  costum_theme()

Our model can now distinguish between 14 different groups. The straight lines show the profit of the men and the dashed lines the profit of the women. Also the colors divide the groups according to ages. This way you can easily see the profit differences of women and men according to their age and it fits with everything we talked about earlier.

Let’s take a look at the residuals and QQ plots:

resid_plot<- linear_model_3 %>% ggplot(aes(x=.fitted,y=.resid)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.2) + geom_hline(yintercept=0) +
  labs(title="RESIDUAL PLOT", y="RESIDUALS", x= "FITTED VALUES")+
  theme_minimal() 
resid_plot + costum_theme() 

resid_qq<- linear_model_3 %>% ggplot(aes(sample=.resid)) +
  geom_qq() + geom_qq_line(col="red") +
  labs(title="QQ PLOT", y="STANDARDIZED RESIDUALS", x= "THEORETICAL QUANTILES")+
  theme_minimal()
resid_qq+ costum_theme()

From these graphs we can conclude that:

  • The residuals plot is looks homoscedastic.
  • Although some points are not placed on the red line at the edges, most of them are indeed placed on this line and therefore a normal distribution can be assumed.

Thanks to the existence of these two assumptions it can be concluded that linearity exists and our model is good for this purpose.

Discussion and summary

We went through different techniques for manipulating and changing the data. We created different types of outputs like boxplot, histograms and more that allowed us to illustrate the questions we asked in a visually convenient way. We also used static tools to analyze the proportion of men and women in managerial positions and check if some variables are depended. Finally, we applied a linear regression model that makes it possible to predict what the median weekly earnings of each person will be by year, age and sex. Of course there are many more questions that can be asked about this data and by using the techniques and tools I have presented here it is possible to answer them.

I myself have learned new things. Although I knew there were differences between the salaries of men and women I did not know how significant they are. I was also surprised to find this in light of the fact that there are quite a number of women who hold managerial positions. Although there are quite a few reasons that have caused these differences I think awareness of the situation is already a good start to improve it. This project has definitely strengthened my awareness of the matter and I hope it will help me in the future.
